-- Air France, Havas, Orpea, Peugeot, Soitec, Steria: French Equity Preview
-- B y   F r a n k   C o n n e l l y   a n d   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 2010-10-19T06:43:55Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-15/carrefour-france-telecom-natixis-pernod-sopra-french-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in Paris. Stock
symbols are in parentheses after company names. Share prices are
from the last close.  The CAC 40 Index rose 0.2 percent to 3,834.5 yesterday in
Paris.  Air France-KLM Group  (AF FP): Credit Suisse Group AG raised
its recommendation for Europe’s largest airline to “neutral”
from “underperform.” The stock increased 3.9 percent to 12.66
euros.  Aeroports de Paris  (ADP FP): The operator of the French
capital’s Charles de Gaulle and Orly airports said it had
September traffic of 7.5 million passengers, up 5.2 percent from
year-earlier levels. The shares fell 2.1 percent to 62.05 euros.  Groupe Steria SCA  (RIA FP): The computer-services company
said third-quarter revenue rose 8 percent to 402.8 million
euros, and it expects full-year revenue growth of about 1
percent on a like-for-like basis. The stock rose 0.2 percent to
23.14 euros.  Havas SA  (HAV FP): The owner of the Euro RSCG Worldwide
advertising agency said third-quarter revenue rose 5.3 percent
from a year earlier to 368 million euros. The shares rose 5
percent to 3.69 euros.  Orpea SA  (ORP FP): France’s largest commercial retirement-
home operator said in an e-mailed statement that it’s increasing
its 2011 sales target to 1.21 billion euros. The stock gained
1.8 percent to 33.98 euros.  PSA Peugeot Citroen  (UG FP): France’s largest carmaker and
Munich-based Bayerische Motoren Werke AG said they plan to
expand their partnership on hybrid vehicles. Peugeot shares fell
1.3 percent to 27.53 euros.  Soitec  (SOI FP): The maker of substrates used to make
semiconductors reported a 46 percent increase in first-half
revenue to 137.3 million euros and said it was profitable at the
operating level in the period. The shares rose 1.6 percent to
7.48 euros.  Valeo SA  (FR FP): The French auto parts maker bought back
987,335 shares at an average price of 32.4105 euros on Oct. 18
and has requested the assistance of an investment services
provider “in order to achieve certain objectives” related to
its buyback plan. The shares rose 0.9 percent to 34.52 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
